  "prompt": "Does the recommended daily values for micro-nutrients the same for, say, a 110 lb woman and a 200 lb man just like macros?",
  "response": "Recommended daily values for micronutrients (vitamins and minerals) are not necessarily the same for individuals of different weights, sexes, or life stages. Unlike macronutrients (proteins, fats, and carbohydrates), which are often calculated based on body weight and energy expenditure, the recommendations for micronutrients are often set based on age, gender, and specific physiological conditions, such as pregnancy or lactation.\n\nFor example, the Recommended Dietary Allowances (RDAs) for various vitamins and minerals can differ based on sex and age. Generally, men and women have different needs for certain nutrients due to differences in body composition, metabolic rates, and hormonal factors.\n\nIn summary, while macronutrient needs can be more directly correlated with body weight and overall caloric intake, micronutrient needs are influenced by a broader range of factors, and different individuals may require different amounts regardless of weight differences. Always consult dietary guidelines or a healthcare professional for personalized advice.",
